Dan, I agree with your sense of frustration about being led by a bunch of people who do not meet the needs of the poeple. You called them Psychpaths, I call them self serving, uninspired and unwilling to &quot;do the right thing&quot;. Wouldn't it be wonderful if we could have a government that saw the needs of  the everyday people as priority, and didn't get so wrapped up in lofty proclaimations. Wouldn't it be wonderful if we had a government that could see reality from the average person's perspective. One universal truth is that democrat or republican, they're almost all the same in that respect. They just don't give a damn.<br><br>
I once heard Fidel Castro speak about history. He said that history is not the actions of the presidents and leaders of countries, but rather the sum total of all the actions of all the people of the world in each and every day. You, I and the others here and elsewhere, each to a small degree, effect the course of history. I hope, and in my better monments agree that we are moving that course of history in a proper direction. I think it totally important to keep that in mind each day as we do what we do. &quot;Do the right thing&quot;, &quot;Make a difference&quot;.<br><br>
I read a wonderful childrens book &quot;Miss Rumfius&quot;. It is about a woman who's grandfather told her that it is everyone's resonsibility to leave the world a better place than when they arrived. I like that idea.<br><br>
Maybe the VIetnam war was good in that it is there to remind us that the horrors of war are so great that we need to be wary of entering into war again. It certainly does that for me. It is my wish that our government could learn that lesson. 
